"Here are the answers to the questions:\n\n***Question 1: \"How likely is it that Bond will escape from Le Chiffre?\"***\n1. Not very likely\n\nThe passage suggests that Bond is now a prisoner of Le Chiffre and his two gunmen, and that Le Chiffre has the upper hand. Bond has been disarmed and is being searched, which makes it unlikely that he will be able to escape easily.\n\n***Question 2: \"How suspenseful do you find this passage to be?\"***\n6. Very suspenseful\n\nThe passage is suspenseful because it creates a sense of tension and danger. Bond is trying to escape, but he is being thwarted by Le Chiffre and his henchmen. The use of descriptive language, such as \"Like lightning\" and \"very quickly, but somehow delicately\", adds to the sense of urgency and danger. The reader is left wondering what will happen next and whether Bond will be able to escape or not."